1
00:01:37,597 --> 00:01:40,599
[ Man ]
The following is my explanation.

2
00:01:41,602 --> 00:01:43,060
Well...

3
00:01:44,563 --> 00:01:48,231
more of an account
of what happened.

4
00:01:48,358 --> 00:01:51,277
I'd been on my own
for a while...

5
00:01:52,361 --> 00:01:54,196
and getting kind of...

6
00:01:54,322 --> 00:01:57,491
lonely and bored.

7
00:01:57,617 --> 00:01:59,576
Nothing to do all day.

8
00:02:00,995 --> 00:02:03,622
And that's when
I started shadowing.

9
00:02:03,748 --> 00:02:05,957
[ Man #2 ]
"Shadowing"?

10
00:02:06,126 --> 00:02:09,420
[ Man #1 ] Shadowing. Following.
I started to follow people.

11
00:02:09,545 --> 00:02:12,673
- [ Man #2 ] Who?
- Anyone at first. Um —

12
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:15,176
I mean, that was the whole point.
Somebody at random.

13
00:02:15,301 --> 00:02:17,260
Somebody who didn't know
who l was.

14
00:02:18,263 --> 00:02:20,681
[ Man #2 ]
And then?

15
00:02:20,807 --> 00:02:23,975
- [ Man #1 ] And then... nothing.
- "Nothing"?

16
00:02:24,102 --> 00:02:26,562
[ Man #1 ]
Nothing. I'd just see...

17
00:02:26,687 --> 00:02:28,939
where they went, what they did...

18
00:02:29,066 --> 00:02:32,151
and go home afterwards.

19
00:02:32,318 --> 00:02:34,820
[ Man #2 ]
Why'd you do it?

20
00:02:34,947 --> 00:02:37,949
[ Man #1 ]
Um, to see where they went.

21
00:02:38,074 --> 00:02:40,075
Anyone — I mean —

22
00:02:41,829 --> 00:02:44,539
How can l explain?
You ever, um...

23
00:02:46,165 --> 00:02:49,168
been to a football match,
just let your eyes...

24
00:02:50,586 --> 00:02:53,213
go over, drift across
a crowd of people...

25
00:02:54,383 --> 00:02:57,218
and they slowly stop
and fix on one person...

26
00:02:57,343 --> 00:03:01,013
and all of a sudden that person
isn't part of the crowd anymore?

27
00:03:01,181 --> 00:03:04,267
They've become an individual,
just like that.

28
00:03:04,393 --> 00:03:07,311
- [ Snaps Fingers ]
- It just became irresistible.

29
00:03:07,437 --> 00:03:10,356
- So you followed women?
- No, I didn't follow women.

30
00:03:10,481 --> 00:03:12,400
It wasn't a sex thing.
I followed anybody.

31
00:03:12,526 --> 00:03:15,236
I just wanted to see
where they went and what they did.

32
00:03:15,361 --> 00:03:17,905
You were playing secret agent?

33
00:03:18,031 --> 00:03:19,907
No, I'm a writer.

34
00:03:20,032 --> 00:03:22,075
Well, I want to be a writer, anyway.

35
00:03:22,201 --> 00:03:25,996
I was gathering material
for my characters.

36
00:03:26,122 --> 00:03:28,039
Well, to begin with.

37
00:03:28,165 --> 00:03:31,043
After a while,
I spotted the dangers.

38
00:03:31,169 --> 00:03:34,046
I'd become hooked.
I had to start making up rules...

39
00:03:34,171 --> 00:03:37,174
to just try
and keep it under control.

40
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:39,801
"Never follow people for too long."

41
00:03:39,927 --> 00:03:42,471
"Don't follow women
down dark alleys after dark."

42
00:03:42,598 --> 00:03:45,349
You know, stuff like that.

43
00:03:45,474 --> 00:03:48,311
lt was supposed
to just be completely random.

44
00:03:50,104 --> 00:03:52,314
And when it stopped being random...

45
00:03:52,441 --> 00:03:54,901
that's when it started to go wrong.

46
00:03:56,611 --> 00:04:00,072
When I started to follow people...

47
00:04:00,198 --> 00:04:03,409
specific people, when I selected...

48
00:04:03,534 --> 00:04:06,579
a person to follow...

49
00:04:06,705 --> 00:04:08,331
that was when the trouble started.

50
00:04:14,003 --> 00:04:16,755
Other people are interesting to me.
Have you never...

51
00:04:16,882 --> 00:04:19,634
listened to other people's
conversations on the bus...

52
00:04:19,759 --> 00:04:23,428
or on the Tube, seen people,
somebody on the street...

53
00:04:23,596 --> 00:04:26,806
that looks interesting
or is behaving...

54
00:04:26,934 --> 00:04:30,561
slightly... oddly or something
like that and wondered...

55
00:04:30,687 --> 00:04:32,562
what their lives involved,
what they do...

56
00:04:32,689 --> 00:04:35,441
where they come from,
where they go to?

57
00:04:35,567 --> 00:04:37,485
[ Coughing ]

58
00:04:45,201 --> 00:04:47,202
[ Typewriter Keys Clacking ]

59
00:04:57,380 --> 00:05:00,590
You watch somebody's behavior,
and it raises...

60
00:05:00,716 --> 00:05:02,634
a hundred thousand questions...

61
00:05:02,761 --> 00:05:07,181
and I wanted to ask
those questions...

62
00:05:07,307 --> 00:05:10,643
and l wanted to know
what the answers were.

63
00:05:10,769 --> 00:05:13,646
And so I'd follow people
to try and find out.

64
00:05:15,399 --> 00:05:18,651
The most important rule was...

65
00:05:18,776 --> 00:05:22,737
that even if I found out where
somebody worked or where they lived...

66
00:05:22,863 --> 00:05:25,323
then you would never follow
the same person twice.

67
00:05:25,449 --> 00:05:27,993
That was the most important rule.

68
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:30,413
That was the one that I broke first.

69
00:06:36,312 --> 00:06:37,896
Yes?

70
00:06:38,023 --> 00:06:40,524
- Uh, coffee, please.
- Come on. It's lunch.

71
00:06:40,649 --> 00:06:42,901
Uh, toasted cheese sandwich as well.

72
00:07:12,598 --> 00:07:14,557
Mind if I join you?

73
00:07:18,521 --> 00:07:20,230
Who and why?

74
00:07:21,899 --> 00:07:25,735
Hi. Yeah, um, I'll have
a black coffee please, and —

75
00:07:25,862 --> 00:07:27,153
What's that?

76
00:07:27,279 --> 00:07:29,948
Another coffee, black.

77
00:07:33,495 --> 00:07:36,413
You're obviously not a policeman,
so who are you and why are you following me?

78
00:07:36,540 --> 00:07:38,499
I'm sorry. I don't know
what you're talking about.

79
00:07:38,625 --> 00:07:40,793
Don't piss me about.
Who the fuck are you?

80
00:07:42,295 --> 00:07:44,338
Oh, thank you very much.

81
00:07:45,841 --> 00:07:47,132
Sugar?

82
00:08:04,192 --> 00:08:06,067
No, I wasn't —
I wasn't following you.

83
00:08:06,194 --> 00:08:08,487
I — I —
I saw you with your bag.

84
00:08:08,654 --> 00:08:10,613
I just thought
you looked interesting.

85
00:08:10,740 --> 00:08:13,033
- What are you, a faggot?
- No, no. [ Scoffs ]

86
00:08:14,995 --> 00:08:17,204
Okay, to tell you the truth,
I thought you were this guy...

87
00:08:17,329 --> 00:08:19,289
that I was at school with.

88
00:08:19,415 --> 00:08:22,793
I saw you walk in here,
so I followed you in just to see if it was him.

89
00:08:22,918 --> 00:08:25,170
- But it wasn't.
- Why didn't you ask me when you saw me?

90
00:08:25,297 --> 00:08:28,799
'Cause I'd have been embarrassed
if it wasn't the person.

91
00:08:28,925 --> 00:08:31,177
Not as embarrassed
as you are now.

92
00:08:31,302 --> 00:08:33,596
- No, I suppose not.
- What's your name?

93
00:08:33,721 --> 00:08:35,471
Bill.

94
00:08:35,599 --> 00:08:37,932
Well, Bill, what do you do?

95
00:08:38,058 --> 00:08:40,894
- Actually, I'm kind of —
- Between jobs right now. Yeah.

96
00:08:41,020 --> 00:08:43,146
- Yeah. That's right.
- What would you do?

97
00:08:43,273 --> 00:08:45,816
- Don't know.
- Oh, come on, Bill.

98
00:08:45,942 --> 00:08:49,653
Don't be coy. There's some burning
ambition inside you, isn't there?

99
00:08:49,778 --> 00:08:51,864
There's something
of the starving artist in you, no?

100
00:08:51,990 --> 00:08:53,823
- No. No.
- No?

101
00:08:53,950 --> 00:08:55,533
- You're a painter.
- No.
- Photos.

102
00:08:55,659 --> 00:08:57,620
- No.
- Writer.
- No.

103
00:08:57,745 --> 00:08:59,078
- Writer, eh?
- No.

104
00:08:59,206 --> 00:09:01,331
- But you write.
- Not much.

105
00:09:01,457 --> 00:09:03,500
- But sometimes.
- Sometimes. Who doesn't?

106
00:09:03,626 --> 00:09:05,251
Me.

107
00:09:10,966 --> 00:09:14,470
- So you're a writer.
- I didn't say that.

108
00:09:14,596 --> 00:09:16,471
What makes you think
I'm a writer, anyway?

109
00:09:16,597 --> 00:09:18,890
An unemployed 20-something...

110
00:09:19,017 --> 00:09:22,311
who fancies himself a writer —
a real leap into the unknown.

111
00:09:22,437 --> 00:09:25,563
- Well, I'm not a writer.
- But you're interested in people.

112
00:09:25,731 --> 00:09:27,482
- Yeah.
- This person.

113
00:09:27,609 --> 00:09:28,651
Perhaps.

114
00:09:28,777 --> 00:09:30,653
You haven't even
asked me my name yet...

115
00:09:30,778 --> 00:09:33,197
- What's your name?
- or what's in my bag.

116
00:09:33,322 --> 00:09:35,490
- What bag?
- My bag.

117
00:09:35,616 --> 00:09:37,742
The one you've been
looking at all morning.

118
00:09:40,746 --> 00:09:42,705
What's your name,
and what's in your bag?

119
00:09:44,083 --> 00:09:46,042
My name's Cobb.

120
00:09:47,294 --> 00:09:49,254
Take a look for yourself.

121
00:09:54,719 --> 00:09:56,552
What were you expecting?
Drugs?

122
00:09:58,222 --> 00:10:00,098
Why would you nick their old CDs?

123
00:10:00,225 --> 00:10:03,894
Easy to grab a load. Easy to sell.
Totally untraceable.

124
00:10:04,019 --> 00:10:05,937
The other stuff's a bit more tricky.

125
00:10:08,984 --> 00:10:10,942
You don't look like a burglar.

126
00:10:11,068 --> 00:10:13,736
Sounds like a compliment.

127
00:10:13,863 --> 00:10:15,781
Are you interested now?

128
00:10:26,208 --> 00:10:38,971
[ Rings ]

129
00:10:55,904 --> 00:10:57,572
[ Whispering ]
Gloves.

130
00:11:01,910 --> 00:11:04,954
- People don't really do that, do they?
- You'd be surprised.

131
00:11:17,927 --> 00:11:19,677
Does that really work?

132
00:11:19,846 --> 00:11:21,513
Wait and see.

133
00:11:27,687 --> 00:11:29,355
Beginner's luck.

134
00:11:36,571 --> 00:11:38,529
[ Normal Voice ]
See? Nobody home.

135
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:42,201
Okay, first things first.
We need a bag.

136
00:11:42,326 --> 00:11:43,409
[ Whispering ]
A bag?

137
00:11:43,535 --> 00:11:45,495
To carry the stuff in.
Why are you whispering?

138
00:11:45,621 --> 00:11:49,248
- Don't you have one of your own?
- Yeah, it's a big bag
with "swag" written right across it.

139
00:11:49,375 --> 00:11:51,043
Ah, bingo.

140
00:11:52,086 --> 00:11:54,212
Okay. What do you fancy?

141
00:12:05,100 --> 00:12:07,893
- Nothing here of any value.
- You don't seem that concerned.

142
00:12:08,019 --> 00:12:09,894
- I don't do it for the money.
- Why do you do it?

143
00:12:10,020 --> 00:12:13,481
For the adrenaline. And because,
like you, I'm interested in people.

144
00:12:13,607 --> 00:12:15,483
You can tell a lot about people
from their stuff.

145
00:12:15,610 --> 00:12:18,236
- How old would you say these people are?
- Don't know.

146
00:12:18,404 --> 00:12:21,572
You can tell a lot from the futon, for a start.
Young people have futons.

147
00:12:21,698 --> 00:12:24,158
Most people wouldn't be
anywhere near 40 with a futon.

148
00:12:24,284 --> 00:12:26,577
And they've got one laundry bag,
which means...

149
00:12:26,745 --> 00:12:28,496
they're probably very used
to each other.

150
00:12:28,623 --> 00:12:32,167
- Probably about 25, over.
- They could be 20 and have been
living together for years.

151
00:12:32,293 --> 00:12:35,461
Nah. No, look at the books.
They're college-educated.

152
00:12:35,587 --> 00:12:38,214
Probably graduated
when they were 21 or 22.

153
00:12:38,341 --> 00:12:40,341
Moved in together in the last year.

154
00:12:40,467 --> 00:12:43,219
You can tell more from the music.

155
00:12:43,346 --> 00:12:45,139
And here is the box.

156
00:12:45,264 --> 00:12:47,890
- What box?
- Everyone has a box.

157
00:12:48,017 --> 00:12:49,893
With men, it's usually a shoebox.

158
00:12:50,019 --> 00:12:52,937
- Are there valuables in it?
- No. More interesting, more personal.

159
00:12:53,105 --> 00:12:54,939
Things like snapshots, letters...

160
00:12:55,107 --> 00:12:57,650
or trinkets from a Christmas cracker.

161
00:12:57,777 --> 00:12:59,862
See?

162
00:12:59,988 --> 00:13:02,614
Envelope, photo...

163
00:13:02,740 --> 00:13:04,783
little calling cards, notes.

164
00:13:04,908 --> 00:13:08,077
A sort of unconscious collection.
A display.

165
00:13:08,203 --> 00:13:10,913
- What do you mean, "display"?
- Well, display.

166
00:13:11,039 --> 00:13:14,999
Each thing tells something
very intimate about the people.

167
00:13:14,126 --> 00:13:16,294
We're very privileged to see it.
It's very rare.

168
00:13:19,716 --> 00:13:21,841
Hey, hey, hey, hey!
What the —

169
00:13:21,967 --> 00:13:24,594
What the hell'd you do that for?

170
00:13:24,721 --> 00:13:26,263
It's like a diary.

171
00:13:26,389 --> 00:13:29,640
They hide it, but actually they want
someone to see it. That's what I do.

172
00:13:29,808 --> 00:13:31,851
Concealment, display —
flip sides of the same coin.

173
00:13:31,977 --> 00:13:33,978
This way they know
that someone's seen it.

174
00:13:34,105 --> 00:13:37,191
That's what it's all about —
interrupting someone's life...

175
00:13:37,317 --> 00:13:39,775
making them see all the things
they took for granted.

176
00:13:39,903 --> 00:13:42,528
Like when they go back and buy
all this stuff from the shelves...

177
00:13:42,654 --> 00:13:44,615
with the insurance money,
they'll have to think...

178
00:13:44,740 --> 00:13:46,699
for the first time in a long time...

179
00:13:46,826 --> 00:13:49,870
why they wanted all this stuff,
what it's for.

180
00:13:49,995 --> 00:13:51,871
You take it away...

181
00:13:51,998 --> 00:13:54,081
and show them what they had.

182
00:13:58,962 --> 00:14:02,216
Saucy, eh?
Found these in the last flat.

183
00:14:02,341 --> 00:14:06,052
Think I'll just give them
something to chat about.

184
00:14:06,178 --> 00:14:09,680
- Why would you do that?
- She'll find them in his trousers
and ask him what he's been doing.

185
00:14:09,807 --> 00:14:12,893
Yeah, but why would you want
to fuck up their relationship?

186
00:14:13,019 --> 00:14:16,480
Don't you listen?
You take it away...

187
00:14:16,605 --> 00:14:19,024
and show them what they had.

188
00:14:26,823 --> 00:14:29,158
- Fancy a drink?
- You've gotta be joking.

189
00:14:29,284 --> 00:14:31,620
Oh, don't be fooled
by the supermarket label.

190
00:14:31,745 --> 00:14:35,164
I seem to remember I've had this before,
and it was actually quite good.

191
00:14:36,250 --> 00:14:39,752
You'd have had a bit of difficulty
doing this with your gloves on.

192
00:14:43,091 --> 00:14:46,467
- So we actually gonna take anything?
- Anything your heart desires.

193
00:14:46,594 --> 00:14:50,430
Although that's not really the point, is it?
I mean, it's just work.

194
00:14:50,557 --> 00:14:52,890
I thought the whole point of burglary
was taking things.

195
00:14:53,017 --> 00:14:56,562
No, this is the point — breaking in,
entering someone's life...

196
00:14:56,687 --> 00:14:58,605
finding out who they really are.

197
00:14:58,730 --> 00:15:01,149
I mean, don't you just feel it?
Standing here...

198
00:15:01,275 --> 00:15:04,235
drinking their wine —
people we'll never even meet.

199
00:15:04,361 --> 00:15:06,362
[ Door Opens ]

200
00:15:08,073 --> 00:15:10,283
[ Woman ] Would you like a drink?
I've got some wine.

201
00:15:10,409 --> 00:15:13,495
- Holy f—
- Shh!

202
00:15:14,663 --> 00:15:18,542
- You startled us! Are you from the agency,
or are you viewing like us?
- What are you doing in my flat?

203
00:15:18,668 --> 00:15:21,294
- Didn't the agent tell you
we'd be here this afternoon?
- But we're not moving.

204
00:15:21,421 --> 00:15:24,923
You must be the man of the house.
Congratulations. You have a very nice home.

205
00:15:28,219 --> 00:15:31,597
- But we're not moving.
- Really?

206
00:15:31,722 --> 00:15:33,681
Oh, then I should check
with the agent then, love.

207
00:15:33,807 --> 00:15:35,683
Bye.

208
00:15:51,200 --> 00:15:54,620
Shit. We shouldn't have come up here.
We're gonna have to wait ages to get down.

209
00:15:54,745 --> 00:15:56,454
There's a way up here.

210
00:15:58,707 --> 00:16:01,543
Jesus Christ!
Do you think they believed you?

211
00:16:01,668 --> 00:16:03,794
Of course they didn't
fucking believe me.

212
00:16:03,962 --> 00:16:05,880
What the hell
do you think you were doing?

213
00:16:06,006 --> 00:16:08,674
- I caught them on the hop.
We surprised them.
- How do you mean?

214
00:16:08,801 --> 00:16:11,177
That bloke wasn't her boyfriend.
Why do you think he didn't say anything?

215
00:16:11,303 --> 00:16:14,264
No, she was up to no good, and she was
probably glad we weren't her boyfriend.

216
00:16:14,389 --> 00:16:17,058
- You reckon?
- Definitely. Why else would she be home...

217
00:16:17,184 --> 00:16:18,851
in the middle of the afternoon?

218
00:16:18,977 --> 00:16:21,020
No, you just can't plan
for that kind of fucking shit.

219
00:16:21,147 --> 00:16:24,066
We were unlucky.
Don't worry about it. It won't happen again.

220
00:16:24,192 --> 00:16:26,485
- Yeah, well, I'm not so sure.
- Oh, yeah?

221
00:16:26,610 --> 00:16:28,986
Well, next time you can do
the fucking prep work.

222
00:16:29,113 --> 00:16:30,822
- No, no, I didn't mean —
- No, l mean it.

223
00:16:30,990 --> 00:16:32,698
Take your mark, check it out...

224
00:16:32,825 --> 00:16:35,285
for days, months, years, whatever.

225
00:16:35,410 --> 00:16:38,621
- It'll be the next place we hit.
- Yeah, all right.

226
00:16:38,748 --> 00:16:40,666
- Tell you what.
- What?

227
00:16:40,792 --> 00:16:43,293
I feel bad about pulling
the panty routine on that bloke.

228
00:16:43,418 --> 00:16:45,920
She's gonna give him loads of shit,
and she's the one fooling around.

229
00:17:47,817 --> 00:17:49,483
A beer, please.

230
00:18:10,798 --> 00:18:13,424
- Buy you a drink?
- Yeah.

231
00:18:13,593 --> 00:18:16,470
- But you can't sleep with me.
- Why is that?

232
00:18:16,596 --> 00:18:18,637
'Cause I'm with the guy over there.

233
00:18:18,765 --> 00:18:21,892
- [ Indistinct Conversation ]
- Not that bald one.

234
00:18:22,018 --> 00:18:25,187
He'll let you buy me a drink,
but sex is completely out of the question.

235
00:18:25,313 --> 00:18:26,813
[ Scoffs ]

236
00:18:26,939 --> 00:18:29,941
- Still want to buy me that drink?
- No.

237
00:18:30,067 --> 00:18:31,817
[ Both Snicker ]

238
00:18:36,574 --> 00:18:38,909
